

Here's how I'd make this project actually win — not just exist, but dominate the Arabic email marketing tools niche:

Phase 1: Win on content quality (Month 1-2)

The #1 reality of affiliate sites: content is the product. The site is just the delivery mechanism.

    Pick 8-10 core tools (Beehiiv, ConvertKit, Mailchimp, Substack, MailerLite, Brevo, ActiveCampaign, GetResponse, etc.) and write the definitive Arabic review for each. Not 500-word summaries — deep 2000-3000 word reviews with real screenshots, actual testing, honest pros/cons.

    Write 5-6 comparison articles targeting the exact queries people search: "Beehiiv vs ConvertKit", "Mailchimp vs MailerLite", etc. These are the highest-converting pages on any affiliate site.

    Write 3-4 "best of" lists: "أفضل أدوات النشرات البريدية للمبتدئين", "أفضل أدوات الإيميل المجانية", etc.

    This alone puts you ahead of 95% of Arabic content in this niche because almost nobody is doing this properly in Arabic.

Phase 2: Win on SEO (Month 2-3)

    Keyword research in Arabic — use Ahrefs/SEMrush to find every Arabic query about email tools, newsletter platforms, email marketing. The competition in Arabic is incredibly low compared to English.

    Structured data on every page — Review schema, Product schema, FAQ schema. Google will give you rich snippets that competitors don't have.

    Internal linking strategy — every review links to relevant comparisons, every comparison links back to individual reviews. This creates a content web that Google loves.

    Target long-tail Arabic queries — "كيف أبدأ نشرة بريدية", "أرخص أداة إيميل ماركتنج", etc. These have almost zero competition.

    Arabic SEO is an unfair advantage right now — there are very few quality Arabic affiliate sites in any tech niche.

Phase 3: Win on trust (Month 2-4)

    Be genuinely honest — if a tool is bad, say it's bad. Readers remember the site that told them the truth. This builds repeat traffic and word-of-mouth.

    Show real data — "I sent 1000 emails through X tool, here's the deliverability rate." This is what separates a winning affiliate site from a content farm.

    Update content regularly — pricing changes, new features, plan changes. Mark articles with "آخر تحديث: مارس ٢٠٢٦". Stale content kills trust.

    Be transparent about affiliate relationships — you already have this. It actually increases conversions because readers trust you more.

Phase 4: Win on conversion (Month 3-5)

    Optimize CTAs based on data — track which buttons get clicked, which articles convert, which product placements work. Then double down.

    Build an email list — a weekly newsletter about email marketing tips. This gives you a direct channel to your audience that doesn't depend on Google.

    Create lead magnets — "دليل اختيار أداة النشرة البريدية المناسبة" as a free PDF in exchange for email signup.

    Negotiate direct affiliate deals — once you have traffic, go directly to tools and negotiate higher commissions than the default program offers. Some tools pay 30-40% recurring commissions.

Phase 5: Win on moat (Month 4-6+)

    Build a community — a Telegram group or Discord for Arabic email marketers. This creates loyalty and a distribution channel for new content.

    Create original tools — a simple "Email Tool Finder" quiz that recommends a tool based on answers. These go viral and generate tons of backlinks.

    Expand the niche — once you own "email tools in Arabic", expand to landing page builders, marketing automation, CRM tools. Same audience, more revenue.

    YouTube content — Arabic video reviews of email tools. YouTube SEO in Arabic is even less competitive than web search.

Why this wins:

    The Arabic market is underserved — there are almost no quality affiliate sites in Arabic for SaaS tools. You're entering a market with real demand and almost no competition.

    Recurring commissions — email/newsletter tools charge monthly. One conversion can pay you for years. 100 active referrals at $30/month average commission = $3,000/month recurring.

    Content compounds — every article you publish keeps ranking and converting for years. After 50 articles, you have 50 salespeople working 24/7.

    Trust compounds faster in small markets — in English, you compete with thousands. In Arabic, if you become the go-to site, word-of-mouth spreads fast.

Content & Conversion:

    "Best for X" quick-answer boxes — at the top of comparison/best articles, a highlighted box saying "Best overall: Beehiiv" with a CTA. Captures users who don't want to read the full article.

    Pros/cons blocks — styled visual blocks inside reviews. Every good affiliate review site has these.

    Pricing tables — interactive pricing comparison grids. Email tool pricing is confusing (tiers, contacts, features) — a clear table is extremely valuable.

    "Last updated" dates — shows readers the content is fresh. Google also values this.

    Exit-intent or scroll-triggered CTA — a subtle popup or sticky bar suggesting the top-rated tool after someone reads 60% of a review.

    Verdict/summary section — a TL;DR box at the end of every review with the final recommendation + CTA.

SEO & Discovery:

    Programmatic landing pages — auto-generate pages like "/tools/beehiiv" that aggregate all content mentioning that tool (reviews, comparisons, alternatives). Great for SEO.

    FAQ sections — on article pages with FAQ schema. These win Google "People Also Ask" boxes.

    Breadcrumb schema — structured data for breadcrumbs (already have visual breadcrumbs, just need the schema).

    Hreflang tags — if you ever plan English content, this prepares for multi-language SEO.

    Pagination for listing pages — when you have 50+ articles, you'll need paginated listings.

Analytics & Business:

    Affiliate dashboard — a private admin page showing which articles/products get the most clicks. Critical for optimizing revenue.

    A/B testing for CTAs — test different CTA text, colors, placements to improve conversion rates.

    Content performance tracking — integrate with Google Search Console API to see which articles rank and for what keywords.

    Heatmaps — tools like Microsoft Clarity (free) to see where users actually click and scroll.

Trust & Authority:

    Author profiles — even if it's just you, having an author bio with credentials builds trust.

    "How we test" page — detailed methodology page explaining your review process. Top affiliate sites all have this.

    User-submitted ratings — simple 1-5 star ratings (no comments/accounts needed). Adds social proof.

    Timestamps on product data — "Pricing verified: March 2026" on product cards.

Technical:

    Image optimization pipeline — product screenshots, comparison graphics. Visual content converts better than text-only.

    RSS feed — for readers who use feed readers, and for content syndication.

    PWA support — installable on mobile, offline reading capability.

    CDN-level caching — Cloudflare already handles this, but fine-tuning cache rules for static content.

    Core Web Vitals optimization — lazy loading images, font preloading, minimizing layout shift.
